							</msItem>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of approximately 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment.</support>
								<extent rend="visible">225 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>235</height>
										<width>165</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>180/135</height>
										<width>120/60</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>225 folios (+ 3 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 4 at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Not established due to tight binding.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Ink partly fading.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2 3" ruledLines="32" writtenLines="31">
									<p>Pricking and ink ruling are visible. </p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side of folios distinguishable. </p>
									<p>The books of the Torah, which are commented upon, are often written in two columns.</p>
									<p>Rashi's commentary is often arranged in an ornamental design (see e.g. 49v, 52r, 52v, 55r, 59v).</p>
									<p>Folio 225r is written upside down.</p>
									<p>Censorial erasures, folios 68v, 82r.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Ashkenazi square and semi-cursive script of the 15th century, partially punctuated and accentuated.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="scribe">Leṿi Ḥalpan</name>: inscribed, folio 224r.</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Ben Tsiyon ben Refa'el Mitantso</name> and <name type="person" role="owner">Daṿid Merts</name>: inscribed with their names in the contract of sale, with a date of <date calendar="Hebrew">15 Siṿan 283</date> (<date calendar="Gregorian">08 June 1523</date>), folio 225r.</p>
							<p>The same folio contains a record of birth of 4 children of the latter owner, dated from 1523 to 1533.</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Domenico Irosolimitano</name>, Italian censor (active 1585 - 1624): inscribed with his name, <date calendar="Gregorian">1593 </date>(folio 224v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">61</ref>. </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Giovanni Domenico Carretto</name>, Italian censor (active 1600 - 1624): inscribed with his name, 1628 (folio 224v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">100-101</ref>. </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Red leather with gold-tooling, the Harley coat of arms in the centre.</p>
								<p>Spine: 'Pentateuch with Targum &amp; Rashi's Commentary. Hebrew &amp; Aramaic. Brit. Mus. Harleian Ms. 5772.'</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1400" notAfter="1499"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Germany</name>?</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts: inscription by Harley's librarian, <name type="person">Humfrey Wanley</name>, <date calendar="Gregorian">18 Jan. 1723/1724</date>. Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d.1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753 </date>to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
							<date>1753</date>
						</acquisition>
